{{2014–15 Mountain West Conference men's basketball standings}}
The '''2014–15 Boise State Broncos men's basketball team''' represented [[Boise State University]] during the [[2014–15 NCAA Division I men's basketball season]]. The Broncos, led by fifth year head coach [[Leon Rice (basketball)|Leon Rice]], played their home games at [[Taco Bell Arena]] and were a member of the [[Mountain West Conference]]. They finished the season 25–9, 14–4 in Mountain West play to win a share of the Mountain West regular season championship. They advanced to the semifinals of the [[2015 Mountain West Conference Men's Basketball Tournament|Mountain West Tournament]] where they lost to Wyoming. They received an at-large bid to the [[2015 NCAA Men's Division I Basketball Tournament|NCAA Tournament]] where they lost in the First Four to Dayton.

On March 9, the team was ranked #25 in the [[2014–15 NCAA Division I men's basketball rankings|AP Poll]], the first time in the program's history that it was nationally ranked.<ref>{{cite web | author =Dave Southorn | title =Another first for Boise State basketball: Broncos ranked for first time ever | website =[[Idaho Statesman]] | date =March 9, 2015 | url =http://www.idahostatesman.com/2015/03/09/3686233/another-first-for-boise-state.html | accessdate = March 9, 2015}}</ref>

==Previous season==
The [[2013–14 Boise State Broncos men's basketball team|2013–14 Boise State Broncos]] finished the season with an overall record of 21–13, 9–9 in the Mountain West to finish in a tie for fifth place. In the [[2014 Mountain West Conference Men's Basketball Tournament|Mountain West Conference Tournament]], the Broncos defeated [[2013–14 San Jose State Spartans men's basketball team|San Jose State]] and [[2013–14 Nevada Wolf Pack men's basketball team|Nevada]] to advance to the semifinals where they lost to [[2013–14 New Mexico Lobos men's basketball team|New Mexico]]. They were not invited to the NIT and, citing injuries, choose not to accept an invitation to the CBI or CIT.

